<p id="fs-id1170571609293">The following graph of the function <em data-effect="italics">f</em> satisfies <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><munder><mrow><mtext>lim</mtext></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">&#8594;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></munder><mi>f</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><munder><mrow><mtext>lim</mtext></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy="false">&#8594;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></munder><mi>f</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> In the following exercises, for each value of <em data-effect="italics">&#949;</em>, find a value of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> such that the precise definition of limit holds true.</p>
